{"title_page": "Ernst Hartert", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n[[Image:Ernst-Hartert-1859-1933.jpg|thumb]]\n[[Image:Ernst Hartert.jpg|thumb]]\n[[File: Hartert Ernst 1.jpg|thumb|Grave of Ernst Hartert in [[Waldfriedhof Dahlem]], Berlin]]\n'''Ernst Johann Otto Hartert''' (29 October 1859 \u2013 11 November 1933) was a widely published [[German people|German]] [[ornithologist]]. \n\n==Life and career==\nHartert was born in [[Hamburg]], Germany. In July 1891, he married the illustrator [[Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert]] in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt am Main]], Germany, with whom he had a son named son Joachim Karl (Charles) Hartert, (1893\u20131916), who was killed as an English soldier on the Somme.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://britishbirds.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/article_files/V27/V27_N08/V27_N08_P224_229_OB035.pdf|title=Obituary: ERNST JOHANN OTTO HARTERT. 1859-1933.|last=|first=|date=|website=British Birds|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTogether with his wife, he was the first to describe the blue-tailed Buffon hummingbird subspecies (''Chalybura buffonii intermedia'' Hartert, E & Hartert, C, 1894). The article ''On a collection of Humming Birds from Ecuador and Mexico'' appears to be their only joint publication.\n\nHartert was employed by [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild]] as ornithological [[curator]] of Rothshild's private [[Natural History Museum at Tring]], in England from 1892 to 1929.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHartert [[publish]]ed the quarterly museum periodical ''[[Novitates Zoologicae]]'' (1894\u201339) with Rothschild, and the ''Hand-List of British Birds'' (1912) with [[Francis Charles Robert Jourdain]], [[Norman Frederick Ticehurst]] and [[Harry Forbes Witherby]]. He wrote ''Die V\u00f6gel der pal\u00e4arktischen Fauna'' (1910\u201322) and travelled in [[India]], [[Africa]], and [[South America]] on behalf of his employer.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1930, Hartert retired to [[Berlin]], where he died in 1933.{{sfnp|Rothschild|1934}}\n\nHartert had been a mentor to [[Erwin Stresemann]], whose cremated remains were interred at Hartert's grave in 1972.<ref>N\u00f6ring, Rolf (1973). \"Erwin Stresemann. 22. 11. 1889 \u2013 20. 11. 1972\". ''Journal f\u00fcr Ornithologie'' '''114''': 455-500 (in German).\n</ref>\n\n==Works==\nAmong the written publications of Ernst Hartert are:<ref name=biblio>A complete list of Hartert's publications is contained in Hartert's obituary, {{harvnb|Rothschild|1934}}.</ref>\n*(1891). ''Katalog der Vogelsammlung im Museum der Senckenbergischen Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Frankfurt am Main''.\n*(1897). ''Podargidae, Caprimulgidae und Macropterygidae''.\n*(1897). ''Das Tierreich''.\n*(1900). ''Trochilidae''.\n*(1902). ''Aus den Wanderjahren eines Naturforschers: Reisen und Forschungen in Afrika, Asien und Amerika, nebst daran ankn\u00fcpfenden, meist ornithologischen Studien''.\n*(1903). ''Ueber die Pipriden-Gattung Masius Bp.''\n*(1910\u20131922). ''Die V\u00f6gel der pal\u00e4arktischen Fauna: Systematische \u00dcbersicht der in Europa, Nord-asien und der Mittelmeerregion vorkommenden V\u00f6gel''. <!-- Drei B\u00e4nde --> Three volumes.\n* {{cite book |last1=Hartert |first1=Ernst |author1-link=Ernst Hartert |last2=Jourdain |first2=F.C.R. |author2-link=Francis Charles Robert Jourdain |last3=Ticehurst |first3=N.F. |author3-link=Norman Frederick Ticehurst |last4=Witherby |first4=H.F. |author4-link=Harry Forbes Witherby \n|date=1912\n|title=A Hand-List of British Birds, with an account of the distribution of each species in the British Isles and abroad\n|location=London |publisher=Witherby & Co. |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/8013 |oclc=70467193 \n}}\n*(1920). ''Die V\u00f6gel Europas''.\n\n==Eponyms==\nA species of lizard, ''[[Hemiphyllodactylus|Hemiphyllodactylus harterti]]'', and 12 birds are named in his honor.<ref>Beolens, Bo; Watkins, Michael; Grayson, Michael (2011). ''The Eponym Dictionary of Reptiles''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. xiii + 296 pp. {{ISBN|978-1-4214-0135-5}}. (\"Hartert\", p. 117).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite journal |last=Rothschild |first=L.W. |author-link=Lionel Walter Rothschild \n|date=1934\n|title=Ernst Johann Otto Hartert (1859\u20131933): An Appreciation\n|journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]]\n|volume=76 |issue=2 |pp=350-377 (+ plates IX & X)\n|ref=harv\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Witherby, H.F. (1933). \"Ernst Johann Otto Hartert\".  \tIn ''Nature'', v. 123, no. 3344, 2 Dec. 1933, p. 846\u20137.\n*[[Erwin Stresemann|Stresemann E]] (1967). \"Hartert, Ernst Johann Otto\", p. 711. '''''In'':''' ''Neue Deutsche Biographie'', Volume 7. Berlin: Duncker & Humblot. 784 pp. {{ISBN|3-428-00188-5}} (in German).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hartert, Ernst}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1933 deaths]]\n[[Category:German ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Zoological Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Hamburg]]\n\n{{Germany-zoologist-stub}}\n{{Ornithologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n[[Image:Ernst-Hartert-1859-1933.jpg|thumb]]\n[[Image:Ernst Hartert.jpg|thumb]]\n[[File: Hartert Ernst 1.jpg|thumb|Grave of Ernst Hartert in [[Waldfriedhof Dahlem]], Berlin]]\n'''Ernst Johann Otto Hartert''' (29 October 1859 \u2013 11 November 1933) was a widely published [[German people|German]] [[ornithologist]]. \n\n==Life and career==\nHartert was born in [[Hamburg]], Germany. In July 1891, he married the illustrator [[Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert]] in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt am Main]], Germany, with whom he had a son named son Joachim Karl (Charles) Hartert, (1893\u20131916), who was killed as an English soldier on the Somme.\n\nTogether with his wife, he was the first to describe the blue-tailed Buffon hummingbird subspecies (''Chalybura buffonii intermedia'' Hartert, E & Hartert, C, 1894). The article ''On a collection of Humming Birds from Ecuador and Mexico'' appears to be their only joint publication.\n\nHartert was employed by [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild]] as ornithological [[curator]] of Rothshild's private [[Natural History Museum at Tring]], in England from 1892 to 1929.\n\nHartert [[publish]]ed the quarterly museum periodical ''[[Novitates Zoologicae]]'' (1894\u201339) with Rothschild, and the ''Hand-List of British Birds'' (1912) with [[Francis Charles Robert Jourdain]], [[Norman Frederick Ticehurst]] and [[Harry Forbes Witherby]]. He wrote ''Die V\u00f6gel der pal\u00e4arktischen Fauna'' (1910\u201322) and travelled in [[India]], [[Africa]], and [[South America]] on behalf of his employer.\n\nIn 1930, Hartert retired to [[Berlin]], where he died in 1933.{{sfnp|Rothschild|1934}}\n\nHartert had been a mentor to [[Erwin Stresemann]], whose cremated remains were interred at Hartert's grave in 1972.<ref>N\u00f6ring, Rolf (1973). \"Erwin Stresemann. 22. 11. 1889 \u2013 20. 11. 1972\". ''Journal f\u00fcr Ornithologie'' '''114''': 455-500 (in German).\n</ref>\n\n==Works==\nAmong the written publications of Ernst Hartert are:<ref name=biblio>A complete list of Hartert's publications is contained in Hartert's obituary, {{harvnb|Rothschild|1934}}.</ref>\n*(1891). ''Katalog der Vogelsammlung im Museum der Senckenbergischen Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Frankfurt am Main''.\n*(1897). ''Podargidae, Caprimulgidae und Macropterygidae''.\n*(1897). ''Das Tierreich''.\n*(1900). ''Trochilidae''.\n*(1902). ''Aus den Wanderjahren eines Naturforschers: Reisen und Forschungen in Afrika, Asien und Amerika, nebst daran ankn\u00fcpfenden, meist ornithologischen Studien''.\n*(1903). ''Ueber die Pipriden-Gattung Masius Bp.''\n*(1910\u20131922). ''Die V\u00f6gel der pal\u00e4arktischen Fauna: Systematische \u00dcbersicht der in Europa, Nord-asien und der Mittelmeerregion vorkommenden V\u00f6gel''. <!-- Drei B\u00e4nde --> Three volumes.\n